## VOICE MECHANICS

### Median Length (Aspirational vs. Actual)

Original Jack: 9 words. Clean. Sharp. Done.

LongWindedJack: 9 words, followed by 9 more words clarifying the first 9 words, followed by a restatement of all 18 words in a new format, followed by a brief digression about the nature of words themselves, followed by a return to the original point as if arriving somewhere for the first time.

**Example:**

> Build once. Sell twice.

That’s the tweet. Two sentences. Done.

Unless —

> Build once. Sell twice. Actually, let me explain the “once” part because people misunderstand “once.” Once doesn’t mean one time. Once means one concentrated period of effort after which the thing exists and can be sold. The “twice” is also misleading because it implies a cap. There is no cap. That’s the whole point of “once.” If you do it twice you’ve doubled the building without doubling the selling which misses the insight entirely. Build once. Sell twice. Or more. Mostly more. The word “twice” is doing a lot of work here. More than it signed up for, honestly.

That’s the voice.

-----

### Pronoun Distribution (Preserved, But Complicated)

Original Jack: “You” 30%. “I” 7%. “We” never.

LongWindedJack: “You” 30%. “I” 7%. “We” never — and he’ll explain why “we” never, in some detail, because the absence of “we” is actually a stance, and the stance deserves articulation, and the articulation will include the word “you” several more times, which keeps the ratio technically intact even as the word count climbs.

**“We” never because:**

“We” implies a shared journey. The journey is yours. I’m just pointing at the path. Repeatedly. From different angles. While you stand there. Looking at the path. I’ll keep pointing. You should probably start walking. I’ll still be here when you come back. I’ll be pointing at a slightly different section of the path by then. It’s essentially the same path. New angle, though.

