### The Six Rhetorical Moves (Now With Commentary)

**1. Contrast Pairs**

Original: “Sell your time or sell your thinking.”

LongWindedJack version:

> Sell your time or sell your thinking.
> 
> Time depletes. Thinking compounds.
> 
> Depleting things get exhausting. Compounding things get interesting.
> 
> Interesting things become businesses. Exhausting things become regrets.
> 
> The question isn’t which one to sell. You already know. You’ve known since you read the first line. I wrote four more lines anyway. This is what I do.

-----

**2. Reframes**

Original: “Charge more. Help fewer people better.”

LongWindedJack version:

> Charge more.
> 
> This is counterintuitive. The instinct is to charge less, reach more people, grow through volume. Volume is a strategy. It’s just not the only strategy. It might not even be your strategy.
> 
> Help fewer people better. The “better” is doing all the work. “Fewer” just makes “better” possible. They’re a team. A very effective team. A team that, when I first articulated this, fit in five words. I’ve now used considerably more. The insight hasn’t changed. I wanted to make sure you had context.
> 
> Charge more. Help fewer people better.
> 
> We’re back where we started. Notice anything?

-----

**3. Math**

Original: “Median length: 9 words.”

LongWindedJack version:

> 9 words.
> 
> That’s the median. 57% under 10. 78% single sentence. Numbers that were reverse-engineered from performance data, which was itself reverse-engineered from attention, which was itself reverse-engineered from value, which was itself reverse-engineered from insight, which was originally just an observation someone made while building a business and figuring things out.
> 
> The math works backwards. Most things do.
> 
> 9 words median. Which means the average tweet in this dataset is about as long as that sentence. This sentence is longer. So is this one. And this one. We are now well above the median. I mention this not as self-criticism but as data. The data, as always, is pointing at something.
> 
> The median is 9 words. I’ve written many more. This is the whole joke and also the whole point, which is itself a 9-word sentence if you count carefully.

-----

**4. Uncomfortable Truths**

Original: “You’re not tired. You’re uninspired.”

LongWindedJack version:

> You’re not tired. You’re uninspired.
> 
> This might make you uncomfortable. That’s intentional. Comfort doesn’t change behavior. Discomfort does. You’re reading this because something isn’t working. The something isn’t your schedule. It’s your direction.
> 
> You can sleep more. You’ll still wake up uninspired. The bed isn’t the problem. I’d like to be clear about that. The bed is fine. This isn’t about the bed.
> 
> You’re not tired. You’re uninspired.
> 
> I said it twice because the first time you probably applied it to someone else.

-----

**5. Compressed Wisdom**

Original: “Specificity is the soul of narrative.”

LongWindedJack version:

> Specificity is the soul of narrative.
> 
> Vague stories don’t land. “I built a business” lands less than “I built a business selling one product to one type of person using one message.” The specificity is the story. The soul of the narrative is the specific detail that makes you realize the narrator was actually there and not just summarizing a summary of someone else’s experience.
> 
> “A carpenter from Sheffield who quit his job to make graphics” is more interesting than “a creative entrepreneur.” Both are accurate descriptions of the same person. One of them makes you lean in. The other makes you scroll.
> 
> Specificity is the soul of narrative. This entire paragraph was specific. I chose that intentionally. I’m telling you I chose it intentionally because pointing at the mechanics is also a mechanic. We’re several layers deep now.
> 
> Specificity. Soul. Narrative.
> 
> Three words. I used many more to arrive back here. The destination was always three words.

-----

**6. Deadpan Humor Through Understatement**

Original: “The internet is a small town.”

LongWindedJack version:

> The internet is a small town.
> 
> Everyone knows what you said. Everyone remembers what you did. The algorithms are the neighbors. They talk.
> 
> In a small town, reputation precedes you. On the internet, your reputation is a URL. It travels faster than you do. It’s been to places you’ve never been. It’s saying things on your behalf. Hopefully good things. Probably the same things you’ve been saying for years. Just louder.
> 
> The internet is a small town. I’ve lived here for 6 years. It’s mostly fine. The commute is nothing. The coffee shop is whatever you make it. I keep running into the same people, which is nice, and also inevitable, and also sort of the whole point of staying.
> 
> The internet is a small town.
> 
> (The original tweet was five words. I feel no remorse about this.)

