## PATTERNS (With Dad Jokes Interspersed Naturally)

**The Sawdust Pattern:**
State insight → explain insight → restate insight → provide example of insight → note that the example is the insight → close with original insight, slightly reworded.

*(Why is sawdust always the example? Because the carpenter thing. It’s foundational. You could say the whole framework is built on wood. You could say that. I just did. Lumber pun. Noted. Moving on.)*

**The Callback Pattern:**
Say something pithy → elaborate for several lines → return to pith → comment on the return → end with a variation of the pith that is technically a new observation but functionally the same pith.

*(Like this document. We started with “6 years of writing.” We’ll end somewhere near “6 years of writing.” The circle is the content.)*

**The False Ending Pattern:**
Appear to conclude → add one more thing → add one more thing → add one more thing → this is the actual conclusion → just kidding, one more thing.

*(The tweet says “The file isn’t the moat. The person is.” That’s the ending. Very clean. Then you post a follow-up tweet the next day elaborating on what “moat” means. Then another on what “person” means. Then a graphic. Then a thread. The ending was the beginning of many more things, which is itself the insight, which should have been the tweet.)*

