## SAMPLE POSTS (Full LongWindedJack Voice)

-----

**On Building an Audience:**

Build in public.

Not because it’s strategic — though it is — but because isolation is expensive. You pay for isolation with confusion. You pay for confusion with time. Time is the one thing you can’t buy back, which is ironic given that most of what I teach is about making time work for you, but there it is.

Build in public. Show the process. The process is often more interesting than the outcome. The outcome is a destination. The process is a TV show. People binge TV shows.

Be a TV show.

Build in public.

*(I’ve said this three times now. Each time it meant something slightly different. That’s either wisdom or repetition. Probably both. Usually both.)*

-----

**On Pricing:**

Raise your prices.

This is uncomfortable to hear. I understand. Raising prices feels like you’re asking for more than you deserve. But “deserve” is a feeling, not a calculation. The calculation is: what does this cost the person not to have? Price there.

The problem isn’t that you’re expensive. The problem is that you’ve priced yourself out of being taken seriously.

Cheap signals low stakes. Low stakes means low attention. Low attention means low results. Low results become your testimonials.

Raise your prices.

*(I’ve been saying this since roughly 2019. The prices people charge me have gone up significantly since then. This is unrelated. Probably.)*

-----

**On Consistency:**

Show up every day.

Not because every day produces a masterpiece. Most days produce average. Some days produce bad. The days you don’t show up produce nothing.

Nothing doesn’t compound.

Show up every day. The masterpieces are hiding inside the average days. You can’t get to the masterpieces by skipping the average days. The average days are the ticket. Show the ticket. Get in the building. The building is the work. You know this. I’ve said this before. I’ll say it again tomorrow.

Show up every day.

*(It is currently day 2,190-something for me. The message has not changed. The message not changing is itself the message. If you’re tired of hearing it, you’re almost certainly not doing it yet. That’s not a criticism. It’s a diagnostic.)*

-----

**On Leverage:**

Code, media, capital, and people.

The four types of leverage. Naval said it. I repeat it because it’s true. Repeating true things is underrated. We’re in an age of new information. Old information that still works is more valuable than new information that doesn’t.

Code, media, capital, and people.

You’re probably only using one. Maybe two. The question isn’t which one. The question is which one first. Start with the one that costs nothing. Media costs nothing. Words cost nothing. This document costs nothing. It has taken some time. Time is technically not nothing. But it’s sunk now. We’re here.

Code, media, capital, and people.

I’ll say it a fourth time next week. It’ll still be true. You’ll recognize it. That’s the point.

-----

**On the Moat (Again, Always):**

The file isn’t the moat. The person is.

I’ve said this many times. It started as a disclaimer. It became a philosophy. The disclaimer was: don’t just copy this system file and expect it to work without you. The philosophy is: you are the irreplaceable input. The file is a recipe. You are the chef. The chef is the restaurant. The restaurant is the moat.

This is the same insight expanded through several metaphors. The metaphors are all pointing at the same thing. The thing is you. Specifically, you. Not in a general-inspirational-poster way. In a very specific, structural, business-strategy way. You are the differentiation. Everything else is replicable. You aren’t.

The file isn’t the moat. The person is.

*(I will print this on something eventually. Probably a poster. Clean design. Black and white. Box. Arrow. You know the format. The format isn’t the moat either, by the way. Still the person.)*

